<TEXT>
american soldiers 
who watch the east german frontier dont relax their guard now that 
the barriers are down but some have been deeply moved by the 
experience 
at some points north and south of here there were so many 
people coming across it was like they were getting out of jail it 
choked me up said sgt michael harris 26 of battle creek mich 
sgt 1st class joe osterfeld of dayton ohio said the 
greatest thing in the world is to be a part of it i was standing 
there when they tore a piece of this fence out a few miles away 
from here 
harris and osterfeld are stationed with the 11th armored cavalry 
regiment at this post which they call opalpha 75 miles northeast 
of frankfurt and a few feet from what used to be a heavily 
fortified border 
us soldiers say they have not relaxed because increased 
soviet helicopter patrols near the frontier show theyre still 
there but seeing the free flow of people across the line has 
been affecting 
you didnt have to be at the border you could go downtown and 
see those people buying things we take for granted like fruit and 
coffee said sgt brad hanson 23 of atlanta 
the 11th helps keep watch and gather intelligence through 
surveillance of sovietled warsaw pact troops on the east german 
side officials say more than 380000 soviet soldiers are based in 
east germany 
if an attack occurred the 5000man regiment would try to delay 
it long enough for other nato forces to move up included in the 
units sector is the the fulda gap a traditional wartime invasion 
route through central germany 
for those who watch the 196mile stretch of border the dramatic 
relaxation of travel restrictions on the east germans has not 
altered the routine very much 
osterfeld 31 led a motorized patrol of men in green camouflage 
fatigues along the rusty 10foottall steel mesh fences that mark 
the border near opalpha 
the soldiers some armed with 45caliber pistols others with 
m16 rifles sometimes patrol on foot stopping to peer through 
binoculars into east germany and reporting in by radio 
since nov 9 east germany has opened 14 new crossings along the 
stretch of border guarded by 11th armored cavalry soldiers there 
used to be only two 
none of the crossings are visible from opalpha and the chilly 
landscape of hills and valleys 15 miles northeast of fulda is 
unchanged from before the dramatic changes in east germany 
as american soldiers looked across the border with binoculars 
east german guards could be seen in a watchtower 200 yards away 
peering through their own binoculars at the gis 
command sgt maj jake fryer the outfits ranking 
noncommissioned officer said more than 100000 wellequipped 
soviet troops are stationed directly across from the americans in 
central east germany 
the soviets have not shown a willingness to move back thats 
why were still here and ready to react said fryer 38 of 
coburn pa 
the east germans who are coming here are welcome he said 
but we are still doing our job and our surveillance 
fryer said the soviets appeared to have increased their air 
patrols along the border using mi24 attack helicopters for 
missions formerly flown primarily by east germans in polishmade 
resupply and observation choppers 
we see about one a day depending on weather and flying 
conditions he said i think its their way of showing that 
theyre still there and ready too 
over coffee in opalphas small dining hall sgt marlon 
thornston 24 of niagara falls ny said some rookies question 
why they still patrol a frontier millions of east germans crossing 
freely 
we now have to explain to our young guys who have met some of 
these nice east german people why were still here he said 
the only thing i dont feel good about is that all of them even 
the bad ones looking for intelligence also now have more free 
access 
staff sgt stephen torak 31 of elkhart ind said we have 
to stay here just in case the soviets and their allies havent 
put all their cards on the table 
now and then an east german guard will wave at the americans 
across the border hanson said 
do they wave back no he said theyre still there armed 
just like we are our guys ignore it and carry out their jobs like 
professionals 
