<TEXT>
sam and julie morter thought their family 
was complete after having three sons so sam had a vasectomy 
then came the morters daughters triplets 
we just tell everybody we hoped and prayed for a little girl 
and we must have prayed too hard because now we have three said 
morter a technical sergeant stationed at wrightpatterson air 
force base 
the morters always wanted a girl 
their firstborn was a boy jeffy then came johnny then jimmy 
the morters decided three was enough and in july 1987 while he 
was stationed in korea the vasectomy was performed 
morter 29 said a followup test performed by an air force 
surgeon confirmed that the vasectomy was successful 
then came samantha stephanie and sarah who celebrated their 
first birthday nov 19 
last year before prescribing birth control pills as treatment 
for an ovarian cyst ms morters doctor gave her a routine 
pregnancy test even though mrs morter insisted she couldnt 
possibly be expecting 
they said not only are you pregnant youre very pregnant 
morter said we didnt know what that meant 
we found out though his wife said 
after the pregnancy was confirmed morter had his vasectomy 
reexamined a test showed that his sperm count was 30 percent of 
normal instead of zero 
doctors arent sure why the vasectomy failed morter said 
they said theyd have to go back in and look he said he 
told them not to bother 
after the triplets arrived mrs morter 28 had her fallopian 
tubes tied dr jan bernie a dayton urologist said vasectomy 
failure is not very common at all ive done them for 20 years 
and maybe one or two in all that time has failed its a very 
effective method of birth control 
in morters case one of the tubes that carry the sperm from the 
testicles probably grew back together bernie said 
