<TEXT>
japanese and americans trust each other less and 
less and an increasing number are pessimistic about the 
relationship between their countries according to a new poll 
japanese still trust the united states more than any other 
country but japan ranks only no 11 among countries americans 
trust according to the poll published tuesday by japans largest 
daily newspaper 
according to the survey former presidents kennedy and reagan 
have left strong impressions on many japanese but nearly eight in 
10 americans cannot name a single japanese individual who has stuck 
in their minds 
the poll was conducted by the paper yomiuri shimbun and the 
american gallup polling organization the yomiuri said 3000 
japanese were surveyed in late september and 1025 americans in 
midoctober a margin for error was not given 
with trade tensions between the two countries on the rise more 
americans than ever before in annual polls 11year history called 
relations between the united states and japan bad 
among americans 93 percent said relations were bad compared 
to 60 percent last year among japanese traditionally more 
pessimistic on the issue 184 percent said relations were bad 
slightly up from 175 percent in 1988 
many americans still feel relations are good or very 
good 456 percent compared to 38 percent of japanese among 
the japanese polled just 31 percent believed relations will 
improve compared to 52 percent of americans 
only 151 percent of americans named japan among the five 
countries they most trusted up slightly from last year but far 
below the 234 percent in 1984 nearly 54 percent of japanese said 
they trusted the united states down from last year and lower than 
the 574 percent in 1984 
americans in the poll expressed the most trust for canada 
britain australia and switzerland japanese gave top 
trustworthiness rankings to the united states britain australia 
and france 
asked if their government should protect domestic industries by 
restricting imports 66 percent of americans said yes compared to 
43 percent of japanese 
on agriculture 64 percent of americans said their government 
should restrict imports compared to 60 percent of japanese both 
figures were up from last year 
among the japanese polled 82 percent said they would choose a 
domestically made product over an import compared to 73 percent of 
the americans 
asked to name a japanese person who had made an impression on 
them most of the americans came up blank 
the late emperor hirohito was the most prominent japanese in 
american minds although he was named by just 66 percent of those 
polled 
next was sony corp chairman akio morita considered an 
unusually highprofile figure in japanese business circles he 
still left an impression on only 16 percent of the americans 
polled 
by contrast 338 percent of japanese said john f kennedy made 
an impression on them followed by 233 percent for reagan and 170 
percent for gen douglas macarthur who was supreme commander of 
us forces occupying japan after world war ii 
americans saw their own leaders somewhat as the japanese did 
ranking kennedy and reagan highest followed by martin luther king 
jr 
president bush ranked eighth most impressive to americans and 
ninth to japanese 
