nov 26 
the flint mich journal on faith and spiritual values 
baby boomers who filled church and synagogue pews as children in 
the 1950s are returning to the fold with their children this is 
good news indeed for a nation that often struggles awkwardly with 
religion and the crucial role it plays in our lives 
in a study presented to the american academy of religion 
sociologists wade clark roof and david roozen found that 40 percent 
of those born between 1945 and 1954 said they were attending 
worship services regularly last year only 33 percent of this same 
generation reported regular attendance in the early 1970s 
perhaps they are discovering or rediscovering the imph and spiritual 
values not only for themselves and their 
families but for society as a whole 
