<TEXT>
shell oil has agreed to pay 1975 
million in penalties and compensation for a 1988 spill of more than 
400000 gallons of crude oil that fouled a scenic waterway near san 
francisco the mayor says 
mayor mike menesini said tuesday the agreement is the largest 
oil spill settlement in california history 
it provides a clear warning that harm to our environment will 
not be tolerated he said 
the spill fouled a 15mile stretch of the carquinez strait 
shoreline and a marsh next to shells refinery it killed at least 
300 birds and animals 
menesini said shell will pay 11 million to restore damaged 
wetlands and an additional 47 million in civil penalties for 
violating federal rules in allowing the oil to bypass a collection 
dike and pour into the waterway 40 miles northeast of san francisco 
the settlement also will pay for such things as environmental 
studies of the affected areas and restoration of the fishing 
industry 
the oil company admitted that it illegally allowed storm water 
to drain from the top of a 125 million gallon oil storage tank 
and that oil leaked through a flexible pipe in the middle of the 
tank and made its way into the waterway 
shell had ignored a federal requirement to monitor the drainage 
system before making discharges allong discharges to go directly 
into state waters 
additional settlement details were to be released at a news 
conference in san francisco this afternoon 
