<TEXT>
a deadlocked jury prompted a judge to 
declare a mistrial wednesday in the racketeering case of three 
1970s radicals two days after they were cleared of charges of 
plotting to overthrow the government 
us district judge william young granted a defense motion for a 
mistrial after the jury announced for the third straight day it was 
unable to decide whether the groups alleged bombing exploits 
constituted racketeering 
prosecutors claim raymond levasseur his wife patricia and 
richard williams were part of a group operating under the names 
united freedom front and sam melvillejonathan jackson unit that 
took responsibility for a string of bombings and bank robberies 
along the east coast from 1976 to 1984 
one of the bombings at a courthouse in boston in 1976 cost one 
man his lower leg some other bombs failed to explode 
raymond levasseur and williams already are serving lengthy terms 
for convictions in connection with some of the bombings 
levasseurs wife is free on bail after serving 3 years of a 
fiveyear term for harboring a fugitive her husband 
young set a hearing jan 5 in boston at which time the 
government will decide whether to retry the racketeering conspiracy 
charges 
defense attorney elizabeth fink called for an end to the 
proceedings 
what we ask is that everybody call us attorney wayne budd 
that everybody call the department of justice and ask that this 
farce this fiasco be stopped fink said 
assistant us attorney michael loucks declined to comment after 
the mistrial was declared 
on monday after 19 days of deliberations in the yearlong trial 
jurors delivered a partial verdict acquitting the trio of seditious 
conspiracy to overthrow the us government at the time jurors 
said they seriously doubted they could reach agreement on the 
racketeering charges 
the defendants had no visible reaction as the mistrial was 
announced but immediately handed out a prepared statement claiming 
the government had suffered a significant loss 
we commend the courage of the jury in the face of a very 
vindictive and politically motivated prosecution the statement 
said 
jurors had already cleared mrs levasseur of racketeering and 
were deciding the same charge against the two men as well as a 
charge of racketeering conspiracy against all three each count 
carries a maximum penalty of 20 years and 20000 in fines 
the racketeering charges include 15 successful or attempted 
bombings of courthouses banks corporate offices and military 
recruiting and reserve centers 
originally eight people were indicted some charges were later 
dropped and other defendants have been convicted in separate trials 
on some of the bombings the springfield prosecution pulled the 
case together through racketeering laws that allow several people 
to be tried for incidents occurring in several states 
