<TEXT>
the nuclear industry on wednesday applauded 
the energy departments decision to sue nevada over its refusal to 
allow construction of a highlevel nuclear waste dump nevadas 
governor said were not going to be influenced by threats 
the department announced tuesday night it would give nevada 30 
days to grant the environmental permits needed to study the 
proposed dump site at yucca mountain after that the justice 
department will take the state to court deputy secretary henson 
moore told a nuclear industry meeting in san francisco 
gov bob miller said wednesday the state would not back down 
from its opposition to the dump which would entomb tons of 
radioactive wastes for 10000 years 
were not going to be influenced by threats when we have 
already taken conclusive and decisive action in expressing our 
opposition to the dump miller said in a telephone interview 
they want us to take this like a dose of castor oil he 
said but this isnt castor oil they want us to swallow this is 
poison 
nevada has fought the project since congress declared in 1987 
that yucca mountain situated about 100 miles northwest of las 
vegas would be the only site considered for a dump earlier this 
year the nevada legislature passed a bill prohibiting the federal 
government from placing any highlevel nuclear waste in the state 
moore said the department had given up trying to persuade miller 
to drop his states opposition to the project 
court is not our preferred course of action but enough is 
enough moore said 
moore also announced that energy secretary james d watkins had 
decided after lengthy review of the yucca mountain project that all 
subsurface testing of the site would be put off for two years 
that in combination with other changes in the project means the 
dump will not open before 2010 moore said 
the department originally planned to the open the dump by 1998 
last year it pushed the target date back to 2003 but failure to 
complete surfacebased testing and nevadas refusal to grant 
environmental permits has forced a further delay 
nuclear industry groups cheered moores announcement despite 
the fact that it pushes back by seven years the date when utilities 
can get rid of the tons of highlevel waste they have been 
temporarily storing at reactor sites for three decades 
the announced delay in the completion of the waste repository 
is regrettable said the us council for energy awareness the 
nuclear industrys main lobby group but the important thing is 
that doe has a plan that puts us on a path toward resolving the 
administrative and political problems 
the edison electric institute the trade group of investorowned 
electric utilities said it was pleased that watkins had developed 
a plan to revitalize the project 
we have long recognized that the repository would be delayed 
we just hope that the new schedule is realistic said david 
swanson the groups senior vice president 
moores announcement also brings to the fore a related dispute 
between the state and federal governments over whether to build an 
interim dump for nuclear waste 
the interim facility originally was proposed for tennessee but 
the state fought the project and congress ordered a special 
commission to recommend how to proceed the commission earlier this 
month told congress that some form of interim storage was needed 
because of uncertainty about opening the nevada dump but it made 
no recommendation on where the interim facility should be built 
moore said the department would press congress for legislation 
to build an interim facility 
moore also announced that watkins had sent to the white house a 
suggested nominee to be director of the civilian nuclear waste 
management office which has been without a permanent director for 
two years department officials on wednesday declined to identify 
the proposed nominee but congressional and other sources have said 
it is john bartlett a former nuclear engineeering executive 
jacqueline johnson a department spokesman said bartlett has 
been hired as a consultant to watkins on waste management 
issues she declined to elaborate 
