yugoslavias largest republic 
serbia urged all its organizations to sever ties with rival 
slovenia on wednesday in what analysts said may be the first step 
toward the breakup of communist yugoslavia 
the move came after the northern republic of slovenia introduced 
emergency measures to prevent a mass rally planned for friday by 
serb nationalists seeking to topple slovenias liberal leadership 
organizers had predicted at least 40000 people from serbia 
would travel to the rally in ljubljana the slovenian capital 
the serbian socialist alliance issued a proclamation calling on 
all serbian institutions and enterprises to break all contacts 
with slovenia 
the alliance a communistled mass organization serves as a 
mouthpiece for the republics ambitious president slobodan 
milosevic 
it said serbs will no longer allow themselves to be 
humiliated by slovenia and that all freedoms and human rights 
have been suspended there 
the state tanjug news agency carried a statement from the 
rallys organizing committee calling off the rally because we 
dont want to be greeted by clubs and rifles 
slovenian tv called serbias decision senseless and said the 
serbian leadership has reached the lowest possible moral and 
political level 
western diplomats speaking on condition of anonymity consider 
serbias move as a first step toward disintegration of yugoslavia 
the country is a loose confederation of six republics and two 
provinces containing many different nationalities and religious 
groups economic problems and sinking living standards have 
heightened ethnic tensions 
a commentary broadcast nationwide on an evening newscast said 
serbias decision complicated the political situation in the 
country to an extreme 
slovenian police said earlier wednesday they would block all 
vehicles carrying serbian demonstrators to the rally in ljubljana 
they announced other emergency measures including banning all 
public rallies and gatherings of more than 30 people without 
explicit approval by authorities 
