<TEXT>
tests on a sample of air duct contaminated 
with plutonium dust at the rocky flats nuclear weapons plant have 
revealed only a fraction of the plutonium inspectors had feared was 
present officials said 
laboratory tests found only 1 percent as much of the highly 
radioactive element as inspectors estimated in august a department 
of energy official at the plant said tuesday 
rocky flats is the only government plant at which plutonium 
triggers for nuclear weapons are made the plant 16 miles 
northwest of denver is operated by rockwell corp for doe 
in august doe inspectors said they found 11 pounds of plutonium 
in air ducts at the plant one of the most serious recent 
allegations about dangerous practices at the plant 
rocky flats safety and hazardous waste disposal practices have 
come under intense scrutiny in recent months fbi agents and 
environmental protection agency inspectors raided the plant on june 
6 looking for evidence of illegal waste disposal and a special 
federal grand jury convened aug 1 to examine the allegations 
the inspectors said enough plutonium dust could be clumped 
together in the air ducts to cause an uncontrolled nuclear chain 
reaction although no evidence has been found that such a reaction 
occurred 
inspectors had said they found one section of duct that 
contained 1600 grams or 56 ounces of plutonium per linear foot 
said david simonson the does rocky flats manager but a detailed 
lab analysis showed the section contained just 24 grams or 084 of 
an ounce per linear foot he said 
however simonson said an analysis of one section of the duct is 
not enough to say eureka the problem is solved and more 
studies are being done 
in all about 11 pounds of plutonium was estimated to be in the 
air ducts in buildings where plutonium is processed and fabricated 
but officials now think the ducts contain only 2 ounces of 
plutonium 
doe has ordered improvements in filters and filter seals said 
simonson also an additional nine engineers are being assigned to 
safety and ducts containing more than 70 grams or 245 ounces of 
plutonium per linear foot are being removed and replaced 
