<TEXT>
along with the holiday festivities it brings 
december poses some of the toughest challenges of all in the battle 
to manage your money 
the rush of giftbuying partygiving and holiday travel can 
easily bust a budget that has been judiciously managed through the 
other 11 months of the year 
experts on the subject have no single magic formula to offer 
that will see you through the holidays with your finances 
unscathed friendships family or business circumstances may 
dictate that you must spend more money at this time of year than 
you otherwise would 
but financial advisers do suggest that your chances of staying 
solvent will improve drastically if you have an organized plan 
its wise to set up a budget before starting to shop 
counsels the american bankers association 
in addition to funds set aside for gifts consumers should 
allow for extra expenses unique to the holiday season such as food 
for parties and out of town guests cards and postage wrapping 
paper and decorations 
adds the newsletter 100 highest yields in north palm beach 
fla put the same number crunching to a trip to visit the 
grandparents or escape the cold weather 
what you dont want to do is run up a huge tab on your cards 
or draw down your savings the mastercard or visa bill will hang 
over your head for months even worse you may need cash for an 
emergency and not have it 
the season can be especially treacherous for anyone walking 
around with a wallet full of credit cards 
buying with a credit card is an added convenience during the 
busy holidays especially with long lines and harried salespeople 
to contend with the aba says 
however consumers should keep a wary eye on impulse buying by 
setting a limit on how much they intend to charge on their cards 
and sticking to it 
if you are among the approximately twothirds of all bankcard 
holders who dont pay off the full balance due each month there is 
an added incentive this year to keep a rein on credit purchases 
credit card interest which always has been expensive will get 
more so jan 1 under a change mandated by the tax reform act of 
1986 in 1989 20 percent of personal interest is still 
taxdeductible next year the percentage drops to 10 percent 
before going to zero in 1991 
for consumers who dont ordinarily work with a defined 
budget the aba says a general guideline is that credit 
obligations including credit cards car payments and student or 
personal loans should not exceed 10 to 15 percent of takehome 
pay 
these credit expenses plus mortgage or rent payments should 
not exceed 35 to 40 percent of gross income 
adroit holiday moneymanagement can have multiple rewards in 
the waning days of the year money that isnt spent shopping can be 
used for charitable contributions mortgage payments state and 
local taxes or any number of other things that might qualify as 
deductions on your 1989 tax return 
such planning may not do much to make your holiday merrier but 
it can be considered an investment toward a happy new year 
