<TEXT>
federal authorities probing trading abuses at the 
citys commodity exchange reportedly have expanded the 
investigation to include stockindex futures trading at the chicago 
mercantile exchange 
separately the merc said it had expelled and fined 100000 a 
trader who previously pleaded guilty to federal charges 
six traders from the mercs standard amp poors 500 index futures 
pit received subpoenas earlier this week to testify before a 
federal grand jury regarding trades they made during the 1987 
stockmarket crash the wall street journal reported in wednesdays 
editions 
the chicago suntimes said at least seven sampp 500 traders had 
received subpoenas and two more were expected to be called before 
the grand jury 
the newspapers both citing unidentified sources said the 
subpoenas represented a widening of an investigation that so far 
has resulted in the indictments of 47 traders and one clerk at the 
merc and the chicago board of trade 
us attorney anton valukas declined comment on the reports 
andrew yemma a chicago mercantile exchange spokesman said he 
could not confirm the reports 
weve always been aware that it is a continuing 
investigation yemma said 
until this week the investigation had been confined to traders 
in the mercs japanese yen and swiss franc trading pits and in the 
chicago board of trades soybean and us treasury bond pits 
in those cases fbi agents worked undercover as traders for more 
than two years to gather evidence of alleged cheating of customers 
by brokers while executing their orders in the pits 
in contrast the new twist in the investigation reportedly 
targets traders who already have been disciplined by the merc for 
alleged trading abuses during the october 1987 stock market crash 
stockindex futures are contracts to buy or sell baskets of 
stocks such as those represented by the sampp 500 index for a 
specified price on a future date index futures are used variously 
for hedging against losses in the stock market and for speculating 
on the markets movements 
the mercs sampp 500 pit is the worlds largest and most active 
stockindex futures market 
stockindex futures are frequently used in computerized program 
strategies that some experts believe contributed to the oct 19 
1987 stock market crash and the market decline of last oct 13 
in one such strategy known as index arbitrage traders move huge 
amounts of stock rapidly in attempts to profit from brief 
discrepancies between prices of stocks and the index futures other 
program trading strategies also have been blamed for contributing 
to the severity of the markets downturns 
however the futures industry contends the index futures markets 
provided a relief valve for selling during those steep market drops 
and prevented the stock market from falling even further 
in a statement the merc said it had expelled brian sledz one 
of the 21 traders of japanese yen futures indicted on aug 2 and 
fined him 100000 for making prearranged trades with his brother 
james in april 1987 
the merc said brian sledz participated in an ongoing pattern 
of illegal transactions in which brokers deliberately converted 
customer funds and market opportunities to their own use and the 
use of others 
the sledz brothers were among the first of the traders indicted 
last august to reach plea agreements with federal prosecutors 
brian sledz has pleaded guilty to one count of wire fraud and one 
count of violating the commodities exchange act james sledz has 
pleaded guilty to one count of mail fraud and one count of 
violating the commodities exchange act 
the merc said the offenses for which it expelled brian sledz 
were the same as the federal offenses to which he has pleaded 
guilty 
</TEXT>
