<TEXT>
the interior department said wednesday it will 
renew controversial longterm water contracts in central 
california assuring farmers will get the current volume of 
irrigation water well into the next century 
at the same time interior secretary manuel lujan directed a 
formal environmental review of how the massive diversion of federal 
water for irrigation affects the environment 
but officials acknowleged the review will not hold up contract 
renewals nor affect the duration of the new water leases or the 
amount of water supplied 
lujan did say the price of the water will more than quadruple 
and price and other terms could be affected by the review 
lujan said the leases would commit the government to supplying 
current levels of water 15 million acrefeet or 489 billion 
gallons per year to scores of local irrigation districts in the 
san joaquin river basin over the next 40 years an acrefoot or 
326000 gallons is about what a family of five uses at home in a 
year 
the renewal of the california water contracts one of the 
thorniest water issues in the west has developed into a major 
environmental test for the bush administration 
the administration has been split on the issue with the 
environmental protection agency and the presidents council on 
environmental quality supported by environmental groups arguing 
that formal environmental reviews should be conducted before the 
government commits itself to renewal 
one lease to the orange cove irrigation district came due last 
april and was renewed amid strong criticism from environmentalists 
several of the leases are expected to be up for renewal within 
weeks 
the interior department said the contracts when renewed would be 
subject to adjustments based on the findings in the 
environmental review these adjustments could included changes in 
water price requirements for increased conservation and manner of 
delivery 
but interior spokesman steve goldstein said the 40year lease 
duration and the quantity of water 15 million acrefeet a year 
would not be subject to change 
under the plan announced wednesday a formal study would be 
initiated to determine the effect of the water diversion on 
wildlife water quality and natural resources in additon the 
departments fish and wildlife service will study the effect on 
endangered species 
at a news conference in fresno calif rep charles pashayan 
rcalif whose district is in the san joaquin valley called the 
decision a profound victory for farmers 
but rep george miller dcalif chairman of the water power 
and offshore energy resources subcommittee of the house interior 
committee said lujans decision to renew the leases without 
waiting for completion of the environmental studies amounted to a 
case study in duplicity 
what value is an environmental study of the impact of water 
diversion if the amount of water divered is nonnegotiable said 
miller 
the natural resources defense council a longtime opponent of 
the governments policy of selling water to some california farmers 
for 8 an acrefoot when it costs eight to 10 times that much said 
in san francisco it was pleased the department had decided to 
require an environmental impact statement 
but we take strong exception to interiors decision not to 
review the most important terms of the new contracts in its eis 
namely the quantity of water to be diverted from the san joaquin 
river for agricultural purposes consultant karen garrison said 
she added that the group will continue to pursue an eis on all 
the terms 
in a lawsuit against the department filed by environmental 
groups a federal judge in sacramento calif has said any 
contract renewals would be subject to provisons of his eventual 
ruling 
the longterm irrigation leases are expiring at a time when 
california is struggling to develop new water distribution and 
water quality protection plans disputes over water for decades 
have pitted northern californians against those in the southern 
part of the state and citydwellers against farmers 
critics also argue that the large water diversions at belowcost 
prices have kept farmers from conserving water when growing urban 
centers willing to pay high prices for water are having trouble 
arranging future supplies 
</TEXT>
